[Prince Edward\u2014Hastings (provincial electoral district)|Prince Edward\u2014Hastings]]\n| established_title               = Settled\n| established_date                = 1852\n| established_title2              = Incorporated\n| established_date2               = December 1904 (village)\n| established_title3              = Incorporated\n| established_date3               = 1999 (town)\n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"cp2011-Bancroft\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3512061&Geo2=CD&Code2=3512&Data=Count&SearchText=Bancroft&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=Bancroft census profile |publisher=Statistics Canada |work=[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census of Population]] |accessdate=2012-02-29}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = 229.56\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3512061&Geo2=CD&Code2=3512&Data=Count&SearchText=Bancroft&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census: Bancroft (town) |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 3881\n| population_density_km2          = 16.9\n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22125\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22124\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|45|03|N|77|51|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| postal_code_type                = Postal Code\n| postal_code                     = K0L 1C0\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 613 and 343|613 and 343]]\n| website                         = [http://www.town.bancroft.on.ca/ www.town.bancroft.on.ca]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Bancroft''' (b\u00e6\u014bkr\u0252ft/) is a town located on the [[York River (Ontario)|York River]] in [[Hastings County]] in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Ontario]]. It was first settled in the 1850s by [[United Empire Loyalist]]s and Irish immigrants. From the mid-1950s to about 1982 mining was the primary industry. A village until 1999, Bancroft then merged with Dungannon Township to form the Town of Bancroft. The population at the time of the 2016 Census was 3,881.\n\n== History ==\nBy 1823, the government had purchased nearly two million acres of land from the Chippewa and Mississaga First Nations including a tract on the York River in Hastings County which had been established in 1792.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://town.bancroft.on.ca/index.php/living/about-bancroft|title=Bancroft, Ontario - About Bancroft|author=|date=|website=town.bancroft.on.ca|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> The area was mapped in 1835 by explorer [[David Thompson (explorer)|David Thompson]].<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bancroftontario.com/history-bancroft-area/bancroft-history/ |title=The History of Bancroft, Ontario |website=bancroftontario.com |accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first family to build a cabin here, the Clarks in 1853, did so to take advantage of the fur trade.  Early settlers included James Cleak and Alfred Barker from England who arrived in 1855, settling on Quarry Lake. They got jobs in administration; Cleak opened a small store and  Barker became the first postmaster. Over the years the settlement grew quickly; there were 89 families by 1868.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uXk3yUgj1yYC&pg=PA99&dq=Kingston,+ontario&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiBna2wxr7TAhVL7YMKHfRMD744HhDoAQg3MAQ#v=onepage&q=bancroft%2C%20ontario&f=false| page=28-30 |title=Hidden Ontario: Secrets from Ontario\u2019s Past (second edition)|last=Boyle|first=Terry |date=2011 |accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> Lumber companies arrived to remove timber.\n\nSome of the earliest settlers were [[United Empire Loyalist]]s, but from 1856 to 1861, most were from Ireland, fleeing the problems caused by the [[Great Famine (Ireland)]]; many had farming experience and settled in the Township of Dungannon where the land was fertile. Most of the settlers were attracted to the area by the offer of free {{convert|100|acre|km2|adj=on}} parcels that had been advertised in Great Britain.<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com\"/>\nSome of the residents also sold furs, obtained through [[Animal trapping|trapping]].\n\nThe settlement had various names over the first years, York Mills, York River and York Branch; when the post office opened in 1861 it was called York River.<ref>{{cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Nila|title=Bancroft, a Bonanza of Memories|year=1979|publisher=Bancroft Centennial Committee|page=90|url=http://www.ourroots.ca/e/page.aspx?id=957965}}</ref> A grist mill opened in 1865, gold was discovered in 1866 and other minerals would be discovered later. The first church and two schools were built in 1870  In 1879 the name of the settlement was changed to Bancroft by Senator [[Billa Flint]], after the maiden name of his wife.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Bancroft & District Chamber of Commerce, ''Bancroft District 2006 Destination Guide''</ref><ref name=about>{{cite web |url=http://www.town.bancroft.on.ca/siteengine/activepage.asp?PageID=16 |title=About Bancroft |publisher=Town of Bancroft |accessdate=2010-07-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706192015/http://www.town.bancroft.on.ca/siteengine/activepage.asp?PageID=16 |archive-date=2011-07-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Flint convinced tradesmen to move to the area, which helped to attract more settlers.<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bancroftontario.com/bancroft-history-2/ |title=Bancroft History 2|website=BancroftOntario.com |accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref> A woolen mill began operating in 1884.<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bancroftontario.com/historical-timeline/ |title=Historical Timeline|website=BancroftOntario.com |accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Central Ontario Railway]] arrived in 1900. In 1903, the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway]] connected to the COR north of town at what is now Y Road, referring to the [[wye junction]] joining the two lines. They were beneficial in transporting settlers and goods; the railway would operate until 1982. Bancroft was incorporated as a village in December 1904. The first telephone in the village was at the railway station; it was connected in 1905. Electricity was not available until 1930.<ref name=about/><ref name=\"bancroftontario.com1\"/><ref name=\"bancroftontario.com2\"/>\n\nUranium was discovered in 1949 and construction of the first mine (Faraday) started in 1952. The very large [[Madawaska Mine]] operated until 1982. Other minerals were also mined over the years.<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com1\"/> The closing of the mine caused some economic hardship. In 1999, Bancroft merged with Dungannon Township to form the Town of Bancroft.<ref name=\"bancroftontario.com2\"/>\n\nAs of the Oct 2018 Municipal election, the current Mayor is Paul Jenkins<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://town.bancroft.on.ca/index.php/town-hall/mayor-a-council/meet-the-mayor-a-council|title=Meet the Mayor & Council|website=town.bancroft.on.ca|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>.\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Canada census\n |2016_population=3,881 | 2016_pop_delta=0.0 | 2016_land_area=229.51 | 2016_pop_density=16.9\n |2016_median_age=53.4 | 2016_median_age_m=52.5 | 2016_median_age_f=54.3\n |2016_total_pvt_dwell=1944 | 2016_mean_hh_income= | 2016_access_date=2018-02-19 \n |2011_population=3,880 | 2011_pop_delta=+1.1 | 2011_land_area=229.56 | 2011_pop_density=16.9\n |2011_median_age=49.4 | 2011_median_age_m=47.9 | 2011_median_age_f=50.8\n |2011_total_pvt_dwell=1896 | 2011_mean_hh_income= | 2011_access_date=2012-02-29\n |2006_population=3,838 | 2006_pop_delta=-6.1 | 2006_land_area=227.84 | 2006_pop_density=16.8\n |2006_median_age=47.0 | 2006_median_age_m=45.9 | 2006_median_age_f=48.2\n |2006_total_pvt_dwell=1849 | 2006_mean_hh_income=38,480 | 2006_access_date=2012-02-29\n |2001_population=4,089 | 2001_pop_delta=+0.2 | 2001_land_area=227.85 | 2001_pop_density=17.9\n |2001_median_age=42.5 | 2001_median_age_m=40.9 | 2001_median_age_f=44.0\n |2001_total_pvt_dwell=1915 | 2001_mean_hh_income=29,684 | 2001_access_date=2012-02-29\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|align=centre\n|footnote=<ref>Statistics Canada: [[Canada 1996 Census|1996]], [[Canada 2001 Census|2001]], [[Canada 2006 Census|2006]], [[Canada 2011 Census|2011]], [[Canada 2016 Census|2016]] census</ref>\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]| 4,080\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]| 4,089\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]| 3,838\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]| 3,880\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]| 3,881\n}}\nPrior to amalgamation (1999):\n* Total Population in 1996: 4,080\n** Bancroft (village): 2,554\n** Dungannon (township): 1,526\n* Population in 1991:\n** Bancroft (village): 2,383\n** Dungannon (township): 1,412\n\nMother tongue:<ref name=\"cp2006-Clearview\">{{cite web | publisher = Statistics Canada | title =\n2006 Community Profiles - Community highlights for Clearview |work=[[Canada 2006 Census|2006 Census data]] | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3543005&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=clearview&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Labour&Custom= | accessdate = 2010-12-15}}</ref>\n* English as first language: 96.4%\n* French as first language: 0.8%\n* English and French as first language: 0.3%\n* Other as first language: 2.5%\n\n== Camping and hiking ==\n[[Silent Lake Provincial Park]] nearby south on Highway 28 provides local [[camping]] opportunities. American sportsmen fished and hunted on this private lake for 40 years before it became a park. Silent Lake has a rocky and undeveloped shoreline, a mixed forest and marshes full of birds and wildlife best seen by canoe. A rugged trail circles the lake, and sections of groomed ski trails have been graded for mountain biking.\n\n[[Algonquin Provincial Park]] about an hour away on Highway 62 N - Highway 127 N - Highway 60 W provides camping and [[hiking]] opportunities, beautiful forest and outdoor scenery. Portaging is quite common in this park. Algonquin offers many visitor attractions. Like Silent Lake, Algonquin has a rocky, treed and extensive undeveloped shoreline, a mixed forest and marshes full of birds and wildlife best seen by canoe. The OFSC trails through the park provide easy winter access by snowmobile.\n\nOne of the most common sights is the Canadian Moose.\n\n== Arts ==\nIn 2004, Bancroft won [[TVOntario]]'s \"Most Talented Town in Ontario\" contest. A large number of artists and artisans live in the surrounding area, and exhibit together in events like the \"Fall Studio Tour\".\n\nThe Art Gallery of Bancroft (AGB) is the area's only public not-for profit art gallery. Completely run by dedicated volunteers, the AGB mounts 11-12 exhibitions per year celebrating the work of local and regional artists and artisans. These exhibitions include the popular annual \"Juried Show\" and the annual student show displaying the work of four regional high schools. The gallery gift shop displays the paintings and fine crafts of area artists and the AGB boasts a permanent collection including some of Ontario's finest artists.\n\nThe town is home to the \"Village Playhouse\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bancroftvillageplayhouse.ca|title=The Village Playhouse - Best of the Arts in North Hastings|work=bancroftvillageplayhouse.ca|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref> a theatre which has been hosting sold out plays, musicals and concerts since the early 1990s. Formerly the Bancroft Community Hall, the historical building was once the local jail, court house and library.\n\n== Transportation ==\n[[Image:Old station Bancroft ON.JPG|thumb|225px|right|Old train station (in 2006)]]\n\nBancroft lies at the intersection of two provincial highways, [[Ontario Highway 28|Highway 28]] and [[Ontario Highway 62|Highway 62]], with several other inroads allowing access to the city.\n\nBancroft is served by the [[Bancroft Airport|Jack Brown Airport]], a [[Transport Canada]] Registered Aerodrome (CNW3), with a 2,200 foot (670 m) crushed gravel runway, located immediately adjoining the town. A small airport, it was named after the man who was reeve at the time and instrumental in its construction.  Currently operated by the [[Bancroft Flying Club]], the Jack Brown Airport is freely available to the general public and frequently referred to as The Bancroft Airport. Due to high terrain near both ends of the runway, pilots typically use a non-standard circuit, following the York River valley through the town for departing from runway 12 or landing on runway 30.\n\nThe [[Central Ontario Railway]] arrived in November 1900 connecting Bancroft with Trenton. The railway went through the Musclow-Greenview road and extended behind Birds Creek through a back trail (which is now used for cyclists and fourwheeling) and continued through the town eventually going further away from the town at the 'Y' road division. The line was closed in 1975 and subsequently removed. The [[Bancroft, Irondale and Ottawa Railway]] connected Bancroft with [[Kinmount]], Ontario. The line was purchased by the Canadian Northern Ontario Railway which became part of the Canadian National Railways in 1918. The line was abandoned in 1960.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nThe old train station in Bancroft served as the Chamber of Commerce and Mineral Museum until it was condemned in 2008. The Chamber, Mineral Museum, and Art Gallery relocated to other sites in the town. In 2011, the old station was moved onto a new foundation;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tedfordhousemovers.com/Tedford_House_Movers/Photo_Albums/Pages/Bancroft_Train_Station.html|title=Bancroft Train station lift|work=tedfordhousemovers.com|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref> it is now restored with an addition at the southern end of the building to house the Bancroft Gem and Mineral Club's museum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdougallminerals.com/blog/tag/bancroft-railway-station/|title=Bancroft Railway Station \u00ab  McDougall Minerals|work=mcdougallminerals.com|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref> and a [[caboose]], which is not currently in use.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moosefm.com/chmss/news/use-of-the-caboose/|title=Use of the Caboose - My Bancroft Now|work=moosefm.com|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n===Print===\n*Bancroft Times, an independently-owned weekly (5000 copies, paid circulation) founded 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebancrofttimes.ca|title=Bancroft Times|work=thebancrofttimes.ca|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Bancroft This Week]]\n*North Hastings Advertiser\n\n===Radio===\n\n* FM 97.7 - [[CHMS-FM]] (\"[[Vista Broadcast Group|Moose FM]]\"), [[Adult contemporary music|hot adult contemporary]]\n* FM 99.3 - [[CBLA-FM|CBLA-FM-5]], ''(formerly AM 600 [[List of defunct CBC radio transmitters in Canada|CBLV]])'' [[CBC Radio One]]; rebroadcaster of CBLA-FM [[Toronto]]\n* FM 103.5 - [[CKJJ-FM|CKJJ-FM-4]] ([[United Christian Broadcasters|UCB Canada]]), [[Christian Music]]; rebroadcaster of CKJJ-FM [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]]\n\n===Television===\n*Channel 2: [[CIII-DT|CIII-TV-2]] ([[Global Television Network|Global]]) - analogue rebroadcaster of [[CIII-DT]] Toronto\n*Channel 4: [[CHEX-DT|CHEX-TV-1]] ([[Global Television Network|Global]]) - analogue rebroadcaster of [[CHEX-DT]] [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]]\n\n==Climate==\n<br>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Bancroft\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 11.7\n|Feb record high C = 12.2\n|Mar record high C = 24.4\n|Apr record high C = 30.0\n|May record high C = 33.3\n|Jun record high C = 35.0\n|Jul record high C = 37.8\n|Aug record high C = 36.1\n|Sep record high C = 33.9\n|Oct record high C = 27.8\n|Nov record high C = 23.9\n|Dec record high C = 16.0\n|year record high C = 37.8\n|Jan high C = -5.2\n|Feb high C = -3.1\n|Mar high C = 3.0\n|Apr high C = 10.3\n|May high C = 17.9\n|Jun high C = 22.5\n|Jul high C = 25.1\n|Aug high C = 23.5\n|Sep high C = 19.3\n|Oct high C = 12.8\n|Nov high C = 4.8\n|Dec high C = -2.5\n|year high C = 10.7\n|Jan mean C = \u221210.7\n|Feb mean C = \u22129.5\n|Mar mean C = -2.7\n|Apr mean C = 4.1\n|May mean C = 11.0\n|Jun mean C = 16.0\n|Jul mean C = 18.7\n|Aug mean C = 17.4\n|Sep mean C = 13.2\n|Oct mean C = 7.2\n|Nov mean C = 0.7\n|Dec mean C = \u22127.1\n|year mean C = 4.8\n|Jan low C = -16.5\n|Feb low C = -15.9\n|Mar low C = -8.6\n|Apr low C = -2.0\n|May low C = 4.0\n|Jun low C = 9.4\n|Jul low C = 12.2\n|Aug low C = 11.2\n|Sep low C = 7.1\n|Oct low C = 1.3\n|Nov low C = -3.5\n|Dec low C = -11.9\n|year low C = -1.1\n|Jan record low C = -43.9\n|Feb record low C = -42.2\n|Mar record low C = -38.3\n|Apr record low C = -23.3\n|May record low C = -10.0\n|Jun record low C = -5.0\n|Jul record low C = 0.0\n|Aug record low C = -1.7\n|Sep record low C = -6.7\n|Oct record low C = -16.7\n|Nov record low C = -26.7\n|Dec record low C = -41.1\n|year record low C = -43.9\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 60.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 53.1\n|Mar precipitation mm = 65.8\n|Apr precipitation mm = 63.5\n|May precipitation mm = 81.7\n|Jun precipitation mm = 89.8\n|Jul precipitation mm = 73.8\n|Aug precipitation mm = 86.2\n|Sep precipitation mm = 90.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 78.3\n|Nov precipitation m