2013|isbn=1317796071}}</ref> The rights of film's negatives and copies were bought by the producers of [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', as to prevent eventual new releases of the film that could have damaged the commercial outcome of Kubrik's film; this resulted in ''Sins of Rome'''s withdrawal from market for about thirty years.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Silke Knippschild, Marta Garcia Morcillo|title=Seduction and Power: Antiquity in the Visual and Performing Arts|publisher=A&amp;C Black, 2013|isbn=1441190651}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Massimo Girotti]] as [[Spartacus]]\n*[[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] as Amitis\n*[[Gianna Maria Canale]] as Sabina\n*[[Yves Vincent]] as Ocnomas\n*[[Carlo Ninchi]] as [[Marcus Licinius Crassus]]\n*[[Carlo Giustini]] as Artorige\n*[[Teresa Franchini]] as  Spartacus's Mother\n*[[Vittorio Sanipoli]] as Marcus Virilius Rufus \n*[[Umberto Silvestri]] as  [[Lentulus]] \n*[[Renato Baldini]] as  Gladiator \n*[[Nerio Bernardi]]  \n*[[Cesare Bettarini]]\n\n==Release==\n''Sins of Rome'' was distributed in Italy as ''Spartaco'' by A.P.I. on January 28, 1953.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film grossed a total of 450 million [[Italian lire]] in Italy.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film was released in the United States as ''Sins of Rome'' and in the United Kingdom as ''Spartacus the Gladiator''.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0045183}}\n{{Spartacus}}\n{{Riccardo Freda}}\n\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1950s historical films]]\n[[Category:Peplum films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Riccardo Freda]]\n[[Category:Films about gladiatorial combat]]\n[[Category:Films about rebels]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1st century BC]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Capua]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Third Servile War films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Spartacus]]\n[[Category:Sword and sandal films]]\n\n\n{{1950s-Italy-film-stub}}\n{{adventure-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sins of Rome\n| image          = Spartaco-movie-poster-md.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film_name      = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} -->\n| director       = [[Riccardo Freda]]\n| producer       = Carlo Caiano{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|* Jean Ferrey\n* Maria Bory\n* Gino Visentini{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}}}\n| story          = Maria Bory{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}\n| based_on       = <!-- {{Based on|title of the original work|creator of the original work|additional creator(s), if necessary}} -->\n| starring       = {{plainlist|* [[Massimo Girotti]]\n* [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]]\n* [[Gianna Maria Canale]]\n* [[Yves Vincent]]}}\n| music          = [[Renzo Rossellini]]{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}\n| cinematography = {{plainlist|* [[G\u00e1bor Pog\u00e1ny]]\n* [[Mario Bava]]{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}}}\n| editing        = [[Mario Serandrei]]{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}\n| production_companies = {{plainlist|* A.P.I. Film\n* Consorzio Sparticus Film\n* Es Establisments Sinag\n* [[Rialto Film]]{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}}}}\n| distributor    = A.P.I. (Italy)\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1953|1|28|Italy|ref1=}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}\n| country        = {{plainlist|*Italy\n*France{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}}}\n| language       = \n| budget         = \n| gross          = 450 million lire\n}}\n'''''Sins of Rome''''' ({{lang-it|Spartaco}}) is a 1953 historical drama film directed by [[Riccardo Freda]] and loosely based on the life story of [[Spartacus]].<ref name=\"45-59\">{{cite book|author1=Roberto Chiti |author2=Roberto Poppi |author3=Enrico Lancia |title=Dizionario del cinema italiano: I film|publisher=Gremese, 1991|isbn=8876055487}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Maria Wyke|title=Projecting the Past: Ancient Rome, Cinema and History|publisher=Routledge, 2013|isbn=1317796071}}</ref> The rights of film's negatives and copies were bought by the producers of [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', as to prevent eventual new releases of the film that could have damaged the commercial outcome of Kubrik's film; this resulted in ''Sins of Rome'''s withdrawal from market for about thirty years.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Silke Knippschild, Marta Garcia Morcillo|title=Seduction and Power: Antiquity in the Visual and Performing Arts|publisher=A&amp;C Black, 2013|isbn=1441190651}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Massimo Girotti]] as [[Spartacus]]\n*[[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]] as Amitis\n*[[Gianna Maria Canale]] as Sabina\n*[[Yves Vincent]] as Ocnomas\n*[[Carlo Ninchi]] as [[Marcus Licinius Crassus]]\n*[[Carlo Giustini]] as Artorige\n*[[Teresa Franchini]] as  Spartacus's Mother\n*[[Vittorio Sanipoli]] as Marcus Virilius Rufus \n*[[Umberto Silvestri]] as  [[Lentulus]] \n*[[Renato Baldini]] as  Gladiator \n*[[Nerio Bernardi]]  \n*[[Cesare Bettarini]]\n\n==Release==\n''Sins of Rome'' was distributed in Italy as ''Spartaco'' by A.P.I. on January 28, 1953.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=310}}{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film grossed a total of 450 million [[Italian lire]] in Italy.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}} The film was released in the United States as ''Sins of Rome'' and in the United Kingdom as ''Spartacus the Gladiator''.{{sfn|Curti|2017|p=311}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0045183}}\n{{Spartacus}}\n{{Riccardo Freda}}\n\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1950s historical films]]\n[[Category:Peplum films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Riccardo Freda]]\n[[Category:Films about gladiatorial combat]]\n[[Category:Films about rebels]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1st century BC]]\n[[Category:Films set in ancient Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Capua]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Third Servile War films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Spartacus]]\n[[Category:Sword and sandal films]]\n\n\n{{1950s-Italy-film-stub}}\n{{adventure-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRenzo Rossellini(link changed toRenzo Rossellini (composer)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sins_of_Rome"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Davis (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2001, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/> Back in the reserves, Davis continued to impress and scored four goals in six games between December and February 2002.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He scored another hat-trick in the friendly against [[Drumchapel Amateur F.C.|Drumchapel Amateurs]] in March as United ran out 8\u22120 winners.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Overall, he made 18 league appearances and scored six goals as United won the Premier Reserve League North.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Swindon Town (loan)====\nDavis joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a three-month loan deal in August 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818141949/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Jimmy Davis Signs Three-Month Contract |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=9 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 August, he made his debut in the league game against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] when he replaced [[Danny Invincibile]] in the 84th minute of the 3\u22121 win.<ref name=\"season0203\">{{soccerbase season|23849|2002|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818142232/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Swindon Town 3 Barnsley 1 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=10 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> A week later he made his full debut in the goalless draw with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at [[Bloomfield Road]].<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020822134048/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |archivedate=22 August 2002 |title=Blackpool 0 Swindon Town 0 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=17 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He made 15 appearances for the Division Two side, scoring three goals, although it was not enough to bring anything better than a mid-table finish for [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King's]] side. Davis was keen to accept an offer to extend his deal, but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] recalled him in November 2002. His last game for Swindon Town was on 9 November. After returning to Old Trafford, he was on the bench for United's Premier League match away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November,<ref>{{cite news |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> and was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jimmy Davis\n|          image = \n|        caption = \n|       fullname = James Roger William Davis<ref name=\"hugman\">{{Hugman|4851|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date|1982|2|6|df=y}}<ref name=\"hugman\"/>\n|    birth_place = [[Bromsgrove]], England<ref name=\"bromsgrove\">{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=164 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/164/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|     death_date = {{death date and age|2003|8|9|1982|2|6|df=y}}\n|    death_place = [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|         height = {{height|m=1.73}}<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/><ref name=\"soccerbase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=23849 |url-status=live |title=Jimmy Davis |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm Ltd |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n|       position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<ref name=\"hugman\"/><br/>[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/>\n|    youthyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1999\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]  |caps1 = 0  |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 2001      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] (loan) |caps2 = 7  |goals2 = 0\n|         years3 = 2002      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] (loan)   |caps3 = 13 |goals3 = 2\n|         years4 = 2003      |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)             |caps4 = 0  |goals4 = 0\n|      totalcaps = 20        | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1999      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 1 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 7 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n}}\n'''James Roger William Davis''' (6 February 1982 \u2013 9 August 2003) was a [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He signed for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] as a youth trainee in July 1999 and the following month he signed professional terms with the club. He played numerous times for the youth and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve]] sides at United and was part of the team that won the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] in  May 2000. He had a short spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in 2001 before returning to United and making his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]. He was an England youth international as he progressed from the [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] to the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20s]] during his time at [[Old Trafford]].\n\nDavis spent three months on loan with [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2002 and scored three goals in 15 appearances. He was a mainstay in the reserves on his return to United; his only involvement with the first team after returning was as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a league game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]  and a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] second group stage match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In July 2003, he joined [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on season-long loan. \n\nDavis was killed on the morning on 9 August 2003 when his car was in a collision with a [[Truck|lorry]] whilst travelling southbound on the [[M40 motorway|M40]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. He was due to make his debut for Watford against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] that afternoon. An [[Inquests in England and Wales|inquest]] determined he was travelling at around 120mph at the time of the incident, and was twice the legal [[Driving under the influence#United Kingdom|drink-drive limit]].<ref name=\"inquest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born in [[Bromsgrove]], Worcestershire.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He lived in [[Redditch]] and attended Marlfield Farm First School<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040913183908/http://www.angelfire.com/pro/jimmydavis/Earlyyears.html |archivedate=13 September 2004 |title=Jimmy Davis \u2212 Early Years |publisher=Jimmy Davis Memorial Website |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and later [[RSA Academy Arrow Vale|Arrow Vale High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416083640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hereford/worcs/3170367.stm |archivedate=16 April 2016 |title=Football stars united in grief |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 August 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He played football from an early age, firstly with a [[Cub Scout#United Kingdom|Cub's]] team, and then with junior sides of local clubs [[Feckenham F.C.|Feckenham]] and [[Knowle F.C.|Knowle]].<ref name=\"earlyyears\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Manchester United===\nDavis signed as a youth trainee at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in July 1999.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> He played in the Jersey Tournament in August 1999; he took part in the win versus [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=186 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/186/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> and the defeat against [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=187 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/187/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> At the end of August he signed a professional contract with United.<ref name=\"bromsgrove\"/> On 25 September, Davis scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in the [[Premier Academy League|FA Premier Academy League]] under-19 match against [[Stoke City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"redstat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redstat.co.uk/?PlayerNo=393 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/mCDBU |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Jimmy Davis |work=redStat.co.uk |publisher=redStat \u2212 Manchester United Statistics |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> United won the game 5\u22120.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He played in the 2\u22121 defeat against [[Nottingham Forest F.C. Under-23s, Under-18s and Academy|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[FA Youth Cup]] third round at [[Gigg Lane]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=197 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/197/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> He started to feature for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] more regularly at the beginning on 2000,<ref name=\"redstat\"/> and he scored in the [[Premier Reserve League]] match against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in February.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=174 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/174/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 May, he played in the [[Manchester Senior Cup]] final at [[Boundary Park]]; he replaced [[Darren Fletcher]] as United won 2\u22120 against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler |first1=Cliff |last2=Ponting |first2=Ivan |title=Manchester United Official Yearbook 2000: The Definitive Guide to the 1999\u22122000 Season |page=177 |publisher=Carlton Books Limited |date=June 2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/manchesterunited0000unse/page/177/ |isbn=978-0-2339978-3-4 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDavis featured in the [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] Centenary Youth Tournament in August 2000; he played in four games and scored against [[FC Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]] and [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/> On 28 September, he scored as United beat [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] 8\u22121 in the Manchester Senior Cup.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> His next goal came in the return game with Bury at the end of November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He concluded his season by taking part in a second successive Manchester Senior Cup final.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He started the game against [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City]] but United lost 4\u22121 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Royal Antwerp (loan)====\nIn January 2001, Davis joined [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> United had a relationship with Antwerp at the time that would see young players being loaned to Belgian club to gain first team experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918180653/http://mufclatest.com/whatever-happened-to-royal-antwerp-the-feeder-club-conundrum/ |archivedate=18 September 2019 |title=Whatever happened to Royal Antwerp? The feeder club conundrum |first=Andrew |last=Bruce |publisher=MUFC Latest |date=1 June 2018 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> However, he only made seven appearances for Antwerp and didn't manage to score any goals.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\nDavis made a positive start to the [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]]; he scored a hat-trick for the reserves against [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]] at the end of September 2001, and then scored two more against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Academy|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 1 November.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Four days later, he made his senior debut in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=\"redstat\"/><ref name=\"debutarse\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220908/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/worthington_cup/1637817.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Arsenal win battle of reserves |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 November 2001 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He played the full game but United lost the [[2001\u201302 Football League Cup#Third round|third round]] match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"debutarse\"/> Back in the reserves, Davis continued to impress and scored four goals in six games between December and February 2002.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> He scored another hat-trick in the friendly against [[Drumchapel Amateur F.C.|Drumchapel Amateurs]] in March as United ran out 8\u22120 winners.<ref name=\"redstat\"/> Overall, he made 18 league appearances and scored six goals as United won the Premier Reserve League North.<ref name=\"redstat\"/>\n\n====Swindon Town (loan)====\nDavis joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon]] on a three-month loan deal in August 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818141949/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/today/view/breaking_news_detail/0,,10341~253023,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Jimmy Davis Signs Three-Month Contract |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=9 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 August, he made his debut in the league game against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] when he replaced [[Danny Invincibile]] in the 84th minute of the 3\u22121 win.<ref name=\"season0203\">{{soccerbase season|23849|2002|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020818142232/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~253510,00.html |archivedate=18 August 2002 |title=Swindon Town 3 Barnsley 1 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=10 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> A week later he made his full debut in the goalless draw with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at [[Bloomfield Road]].<ref name=\"season0203\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020822134048/http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk:80/stats/view/postmatch_analysis/0,,10341~257798,00.html |archivedate=22 August 2002 |title=Blackpool 0 Swindon Town 0 |work=SwindonTownFC.co.uk |publisher=Swindon Town Football Club |date=17 August 2002 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He made 15 appearances for the Division Two side, scoring three goals, although it was not enough to bring anything better than a mid-table finish for [[Andy King (footballer, born 1956)|Andy King's]] side. Davis was keen to accept an offer to extend his deal, but United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] recalled him in November 2002. His last game for Swindon Town was on 9 November. After returning to Old Trafford, he was on the bench for United's Premier League match away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 17 November,<ref>{{cite news |title=Defoe denies Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2430783.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> and was again an unused substitute in their [[UEFA Champions League]] second group stage match away to [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 18 March 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deportivo see off Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2856429.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a season-long loan on 8 July 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watford lure Man Utd fledgling |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/watford/3054232.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2003 |accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Under-16===\nDavis represented [[England national under-16 football team|England]] at the [[1999 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]. On 2 May 1999, he featured in the quarter final defeat against host nation [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic]]; he replaced [[Jamie McMaster]] in the 86th minute as England lost 1\u22120 [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|after extra time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722011401/http://nv.fotbal.cz/en-national-teams/national-team-u-16/statistics/viewstat2.asp?page=/nat/16/1998/match15.asp |archivedate=22 July 2018 |title=Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 86 |work=Fotbal.cz |publisher=Fotbalov\u00e9 asociace \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky |language=Czech |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-18===\nDavis played for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18s]] in the win against [[Belgium national under-18 football team|Belgium]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420123850/https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5407330.defoe-given-half-a-game/ |archivedate=20 April 2020 |title=Defoe given half a game |first= |last= |work=Dorset Echo |publisher=Newsquest Media Group Ltd |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Under-20===\nDavis made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] in November 2001; he started the win against [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] at [[St Mary's Stadium]] before being replaced by [[Andrew Johnson (footballer, born 1981)|Andrew Johnson]].<ref name=\"engonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229151245/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |archivedate=29 February 2020 |title=England's Matches the under 20's |work=EnglandFootballOnline.com |publisher=England Football Online \u2212 Chris Goodwin & Glen Isherwood |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2002, he scored two goals in the win against [[Finland national under-20 football team|Finland]] at the [[University of Bolton Stadium|Reebok Stadium]].<ref name=\"engonline\"/> He was a part of the squad that participated in the [[Toulon Tournament]] in May 2002;<ref name=\"espoirs\">{{cite web|url=https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914203846/https://festival-foot-espoirs.com/festival/archives/palmares.php?annee=2002 |archivedate=14 September 2019 |title=30\u00c8 Festival International Espoirs |work=Festival-Foot-Espoirs.com |publisher=Festival International Espoirs |language=French |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> he featured in four games, scoring the winning goal in the group game against Portugal,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313204835/http://www.thefa.com:80/England/U20s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/05/11456.htm |archivedate=13 March 2004 |title=Toulon: Davis on cue to seal victory |first=Lawrie |last=Madden |work=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> as England finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"engonline\"/><ref name=\"espoirs\"/> He received the \"Le joueur le + courtois\" award, translated as being the most courteous player in the tournament.<ref name=\"espoirs\"/> These were his last appearances for the U20s. Overall, Davis earned seven caps and scored three goals.<ref name=\"engonline\"/>\n\n==Death==\nDavis was killed in a car crash on the [[M40 motorway]] in the early hours of 9 August 2003. He crashed his [[BMW]] into a truck and was pronounced dead at the scene. The truck driver suffered minor injuries. The accident occurred just hours before Watford were due to open their season with a match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. The Watford board of directors announced later that morning that the match was postponed due to \"tragic circumstances beyond their control\", though they did not announce Davis' death for another few hours. His funeral took place at Redditch Crematorium, with the Manchester United team in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110522070822/http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-12740453,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 May 2011 |title=Stars Pay Respect To Jimmy Davis |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=23 August 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe subsequent [[inquest]] reported that Davis was more than twice over the legal drink-drive limit and it was believed that he had been driving at speeds of up to 120&nbsp;mph when losing control of his car when he fell asleep at the wheel.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{cite news | url=http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/news/s/83/83016_crash_death_footballer_twice_drink_drive_limit.html | title=Crash death footballer twice drink drive limit | publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> The inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/3529553.stm | title=Under-21 United star over limit | work=BBC News | date=3 March 2004 | accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA few days after his death, Swindon dedicated their 4\u20130 win over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to the young player, with Davis's mother making a speech in front of the Swindon fans before the kick-off. Additionally, Swindon Town took part in a memorial match with his local club [[Redditch United F.C.|Redditch United]]; Swindon won 2\u20131 with [[Sam Parkin]] scoring the goals. Manchester United paid tribute to him during their [[2003 FA Community Shield]] victory against [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]], with both teams wearing black armbands during the match. United also paid tribute to him after their victory in the [[2004 FA Cup Final]], when after the final whistle and before the presentation they changed into shirts printed with Davis's name and squad number, 36, on the back.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3739335.stm | title=Players remember Davis | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=22 May 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n;General\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/05/jimmy-davis-danny-webber-united-watford \"'Jimmy was dead, when as far as I was concerned, he was still in bed'\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 August 2013\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerbase}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051207155002/http://www.manutd.com/bio/bio.sps?iBiographyID=1636 Jimmy Davis] at ManUtd.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bromsgrove]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSwindon Town (loan)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Davis_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Dudley Hooper", "text_new": "[[File:Dudley Hooper.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Dudley Hooper<ref name=\"obituary\" /><ref name=\"bcs\" />]]\n\n'''Dudley W. Hooper''' [[Master of Arts|MA]] [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] (1911 \u2013 12 January 1968) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman in the UK [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) and an early President of the [[British Computer Society]] (BCS). He was an [[accountant]] and an early promoter of [[electronic data processing]] (EDP).\n\nDudley Hooper was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite article| title=Obituary: Dudley W, Hooper, M.A. F.C.A. | first=E. E. | last=Boyles | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=12 | number=1 | date=1969 | page=16 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.1.12 }}</ref> In 1935, he qualified as a [[Chartered Accountant]]. He spent 1940\u201345 on war service, mostly in [[Africa]] and as a [[staff officer]], during [[World War II]].\n\nHooper had training and experience in mathematics, accountancy, and the use and development of office technology.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://archive.org/stream/bitsavers_computersA_8551508/196910_djvu.txt | title=People and Computers \u2014 Part 1 | first=Alfred | last=Robens | authorlink=Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham | journal=[[Computers and Automation]] | date=October 1969 | page=52 | accessdate=20 April 2020 | publisher=[[Archive.org]] }}</ref> He was at the National Coal Board for almost two decades, from 1948 initially as a \ntechnical specialist in the application of [[accounting machine]]s. He served as Chief Organising Accountant of the NCB during 1954\u201364. He then joined the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|Institute of Chartered Accountants]] as Technical Officer. Hooper had his first ideas on [[data processing]] in 1948, about five years before suitable computer equipment was actually available for office applications. He was a pioneer in training business users of computers.\n\nDudley Hooper was involved in the formation of the British Computer Society in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.computerconservationsociety.org/resurrection/res36.htm#f | title=How the BCS Was Born | first=Peter | last=Barnes | journal=[[Computer Resurrection]]: [[The Bulletin of the Computer Conservation Society]] | issn=0958-7403 | volume=36 | date=Autumn 2005 | publisher=[[Computer Conservation Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In April 1956, he chaired a meeting of the [[London Computer Group]] (LCG) at the [[Caxton Hall]] in [[Westminster]], [[London]], formed in the same year. The British Computer Society was formed in 1957 from the merger of the LCG and an association of scientists. Hooper was the first Chairman of British Computer Society and was later the President during 1961\u201362.<ref name=\"bcs\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bcs.org/more/about-us/history-of-bcs/bcs-past-presidents/ | title=BCS past presidents | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Editorial Board]] of ''[[The Computer Journal]]'', the journal of the British Computer Society.<ref name=\"obituary\" /> He was also founder an first editor of ''[[The Computer Bulletin]]'' of the British Computer Society. \n\nHooper lectured at [[Northampton Polytechnic]] (later [[City, University of London|City University]]).<ref name=\"obituary\" />\n\nA '''Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture''' was given in Hooper's memory.<ref>{{cite article| title=Notice: Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=11 | number=3 | date=1968 | page=352 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.3.352 }}</ref> It was delivered on 28 January 1969 by [[Lord Robens of Woldingham]], Chairman of the National Coal Board, at the [[William Beveridge]] Hall, [[University of London]], under the auspices of the British Computer Society.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo|pro}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Yates]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the British Computer Society]]|years=1961\u20131962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sid Michaelson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Frank}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British accountants]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Computer Society]]\n\n{{UK-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dudley Hooper.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Dudley Hooper<ref name=\"obituary\" /><ref name=\"bcs\" />]]\n\n'''Dudley W. Hooper''' [[Master of Arts|MA]] [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|FCA]] (1911 \u2013 12 January 1968) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman in the UK [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) and an early President of the [[British Computer Society]] (BCS). He was an [[accountant]] and an early promoter of [[electronic data processing]] (EDP).\n\nDudley Hooper was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite article| title=Obituary: Dudley W, Hooper, M.A. F.C.A. | first=E. E. | last=Boyles | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=12 | number=1 | date=1969 | page=16 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.1.12 }}</ref> In 1935, he qualified as a [[Chartered Accountant]]. He spent 1940\u201345 on war service, mostly in [[Africa]] and as a [[staff officer]], during [[World War II]].\n\nHooper had training and experience in mathematics, accountancy, and the use and development of office technology.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://archive.org/stream/bitsavers_computersA_8551508/196910_djvu.txt | title=People and Computers \u2014 Part 1 | first=Alfred | last=Robens | authorlink=Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham | journal=[[Computers and Automation]] | date=October 1969 | page=52 | accessdate=20 April 2020 | publisher=[[Archive.org]] }}</ref> He was at the National Coal Board for almost two decades, from 1948 initially as a \ntechnical specialist in the application of [[accounting machine]]s. He served as Chief Organising Accountant of the NCB during 1954\u201364. He then joined the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|Institute of Chartered Accountants]] as Technical Officer. Hooper had his first ideas on [[data processing]] in 1948, about five years before suitable computer equipment was actually available for office applications. he was a pioneer in training business users of computers.\n\nDudley Hooper was involved in the formation of the British Computer Society in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.computerconservationsociety.org/resurrection/res36.htm#f | title=How the BCS Was Born | first=Peter | last=Barnes | journal=[[Computer Resurrection]]: [[The Bulletin of the Computer Conservation Society]] | issn=0958-7403 | volume=36 | date=Autumn 2005 | publisher=[[Computer Conservation Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> In April 1956, he chaired a meeting of the [[London Computer Group]] (LCG) at the [[Caxton Hall]] in [[Westminster]], [[London]], formed in the same year. The British Computer Society was formed in 1957 from the merger of the LCG and an association of scientists. Hooper was the first Chairman of British Computer Society and was later the President during 1961\u201362.<ref name=\"bcs\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bcs.org/more/about-us/history-of-bcs/bcs-past-presidents/ | title=BCS past presidents | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | location=UK | accessdate=20 April 2020 }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Editorial Board]] of ''[[The Computer Journal]]'', the journal of the British Computer Society.<ref name=\"obituary\" /> He was also founder an first editor of ''[[The Computer Bulletin]]'' of the British Computer Society. \n\nHooper lectured at [[Northampton Polytechnic]] (later [[City, University of London|City University]]).<ref name=\"obituary\" />\n\nA '''Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture''' was given in Hooper's memory.<ref>{{cite article| title=Notice: Dudley Hooper Memorial Lecture | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | volume=11 | number=3 | date=1968 | page=352 | publisher=[[British Computer Society]] | doi=10.1093/comjnl/11.3.352 }}</ref> It was delivered on 28 January 1969 by [[Lord Robens of Woldingham]], Chairman of the National Coal Board, at the [[William Beveridge]] Hall, [[University of London]], under the auspices of the British Computer Society.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo|pro}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Yates]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the British Computer Society]]|years=1961\u20131962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sid Michaelson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Frank}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:British accountants]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Computer Society]]\n\n{{UK-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jpbowen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dudley_Hooper"}
{"title_page": "List of Cricket World Cup records", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\nThe [[Cricket World Cup]] is a [[One Day International]] (ODI) competition in men's [[cricket]]. Organised by the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC), the tournament has taken place every four years since it was first held in Cricket World Cup in England. The number of teams and number of matches have increased since then, although the ICC declared an interest in reducing the format,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/england/eng-world-cup,308088,EN.html| title = England learn World Cup fate| date = 7 October 2009| publisher = England and Wales Cricket Board| accessdate = 27 October 2009| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100113012633/http://ecb.co.uk/news/england/eng-world-cup,308088,EN.html| archivedate = 13 January 2010| df = dmy-all}}</ref> following criticism of the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/8306930.stm | title = Mumbai lands 2011 World Cup final | publisher = BBC Sport | accessdate = 27 October 2009 | date = 14 October 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091017051532/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/8306930.stm | archive-date = 17 October 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n[[India national cricket team|Indian]] [[Batting (cricket)|batsman]] [[Sachin Tendulkar]] holds an array of individual records in the World Cup. One of the [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year]] in 1997, and \"the most followed cricketer in the world\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/35320.html |title=Sachin Tendulkar |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=23 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111231090501/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/35320.html |archive-date=31 December 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tendulkar has made more scores over fifty and scored more runs than any other cricketer in World Cup history. [[Australia national cricket team|Australian]] [[Glenn McGrath]] dominates the individual [[Bowling (cricket)|bowling]] records, having featured for his country in four World Cups.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/6565.html?class=2;filter=advanced;orderby=start;template=results;trophy=12;type=allround;view=match | title = Statistics \u2013 Statsguru \u2013 GD McGrath \u2013 One-Day Internationals (World Cup) | publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 27 October 2009}}</ref> He has one of the best strike rate and economy rate among any other bowler, having the best individual bowling figures and taken more wickets in the history of the tournament. \n\nAustralians [[Ricky Ponting]] and [[Adam Gilchrist]] with Sri Lankan [[Kumar Sangakkara]] lead the individual fielding records. Ponting is the leading [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]] in terms of catches taken, in both an individual World Cup tournament and in the competition's history. [[Wicketkeeper]] Gilchrist has made the most [[Dismissal (cricket)|dismissals]] in a single match and individual tournament, while Sangakkara has the most dismissals by a wicketkeeper in World Cup history. Australia hold several team records, including those for the most wins, the highest win percentage, the most consecutive wins; they were undefeated in the 2003 and [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] campaigns.\n\nRecords are also kept of unsuccessful performances. These include [[Canada national cricket team|Canada's]] lowest score in the history of the tournament, [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe's]] record number of matches lost and Canadian [[Nicholas De Groot]]'s three consecutive [[Duck (cricket)|ducks]].\n\n==Notation==\n'''Team notation'''\n* (300\u20133) indicates that a team scored 300 [[run (cricket)|runs]] for three [[wicket]]s and the [[Innings (cricket)|innings]] was closed, either due to a successful [[wikt:run chase|run chase]] or if no [[Over (cricket)|overs]] remained (or are able) to be bowled.\n* (300) indicates that a team scored 300 runs and was all out, either by losing all ten wickets or by having one or more [[batsmen]] unable to bat and losing the remaining wickets.\n\n'''Batting notation'''\n* (100) indicates that a batsman scored 100 runs and was [[dismissal (cricket)|out]].\n* (100*) indicates that a batsman scored 100 runs and was [[not out]].\n\n'''Bowling notation'''\n* (5\u2013100) indicates that a bowler has captured five wickets while giving away 100 runs.\n\n'''Currently playing'''\n* Record holders who are currently playing ODIs or streaks that are still active and can change have a ^ next to their name.\n\n==Team records==\n\n=== Team wins, losses, ties, and no results ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Team\n! colspan=\"2\" |Span\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Matches\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Won\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Lost\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Tied\n! rowspan=\"2\" |No result\n! rowspan=\"2\" |% Win\n|-\n!First Season !!Last Season\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|AFG}}\n|2015||2019 || 15 || 1 || 14 || 0 || 0 || 6.66%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|AUS}}\n|1975 || 2019 || 94 || 69 || 23 || 1 || 1 || 74.73%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|BAN}}\n|1999 || 2019 || 40 || 14 || 25 || 0 || 1 || 35.89%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|BER}}\n|2007 || \u2013 || 3 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 0 ||0.00%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|CAN}}\n|1979 || 2011 || 18 || 2 || 16 || 0 || 0 || 11.11%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flagicon|East Africa}} [[East Africa cricket team|East Africa]]\n|1975 || \u2013 || 3 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 0 || 0.00%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|ENG}}\n|1975 ||2019 ||83 ||48 ||32 ||2 ||1 ||59.75%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|IND}}\n|1975 ||2019 ||84 ||53 ||29 ||1 ||1 ||64.45%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{cr|IRE}}\n|2007 ||2015 ||21 ||7 ||13 ||1 ||0 ||35.71%\n|-\n| style=\